1
00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:07.100
So this means that you have a daddy and a mommy too?

2
00:00:07.100 --> 00:00:11.540
Yes, and they're your grandpa and grandma.

3
00:00:11.540 --> 00:00:12.540
Where are they?

4
00:00:12.540 --> 00:00:13.540
Far away.

5
00:00:13.540 --> 00:00:15.100
Where is far away?

6
00:00:15.100 --> 00:00:16.700
Can we go there?

7
00:00:16.700 --> 00:00:21.620
You know, Adrian, being a daddy or a mommy means loving your children more than anything

8
00:00:21.620 --> 00:00:23.300
in the world.

9
00:00:23.300 --> 00:00:28.300
And there are things that my daddy and my mommy love more than me.

10
00:00:28.300 --> 00:00:31.360
Things that sometimes make them not so good.

11
00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:32.720
That's why we never see them.

12
00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:34.840
Does that mean that daddy doesn't love me?

13
00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:36.620
Why would you say that?

14
00:00:36.620 --> 00:00:38.080
Because we never see daddy.

15
00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:39.080
He's never here.

16
00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:42.380
No, no, it's just that daddy travels a lot.

17
00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:46.540
He goes around the world with Natalie looking for important things.

18
00:00:46.540 --> 00:00:56.660
One day they'll find them and all get better, then we'll all stay home together.

19
00:00:56.660 --> 00:01:02.240
In the daytime, I'm Marinette, just a normal girl with a normal life.

20
00:01:02.240 --> 00:01:30.900
But there's something about me that no one knows yet, because I've got a secret.

21
00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:39.340
Everything all right, Adrian?

22
00:01:39.340 --> 00:01:47.740
I'm sorry, Natalie.

23
00:01:47.740 --> 00:02:02.500
Lunch is ready.

24
00:02:02.500 --> 00:02:03.500
Yes.

25
00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:06.040
Yes, sir.

26
00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:07.700
Yes.

27
00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:10.180
Goodbye.

28
00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:13.020
Everything all right, Natalie?

29
00:02:13.020 --> 00:02:16.220
Your grandparents want to see you.

30
00:02:16.220 --> 00:02:20.140
That's how Bracciolo is done.

31
00:02:20.140 --> 00:02:26.860
I, for one, feel like somebody's missing.

32
00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:27.860
When do we get to meet him?

33
00:02:27.860 --> 00:02:28.860
But dad, you already know him.

34
00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:29.860
You've seen him hundreds of times already.

35
00:02:29.860 --> 00:02:30.860
Oh, the young model.

36
00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:31.860
Handsome as a princess.

37
00:02:31.860 --> 00:02:32.860
Yes, he is very, very, very handsome.

38
00:02:32.860 --> 00:02:33.860
But he's more than that.

39
00:02:33.860 --> 00:02:34.860
And he's not a model anymore, you know.

40
00:02:34.860 --> 00:02:45.380
Well, no, we don't know since you haven't officially introduced him as your boyfriend

41
00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:46.380
to us.

42
00:02:46.380 --> 00:02:51.060
So, I was thinking you could invite him over for lunch on Sunday.

43
00:02:51.060 --> 00:02:52.060
Invite him!

44
00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:53.060
Invite him!

45
00:02:53.060 --> 00:02:54.060
Invite him!

46
00:02:54.060 --> 00:02:55.060
Really?

47
00:02:55.060 --> 00:02:56.060
All of you?

48
00:02:56.060 --> 00:02:57.060
It's our first time being in a relationship.

49
00:02:57.060 --> 00:02:59.480
Let her do things at her own pace.

50
00:02:59.480 --> 00:03:01.900
You can invite him if you want to, sweetheart.

51
00:03:01.900 --> 00:03:04.380
No, it's too soon.

52
00:03:04.380 --> 00:03:07.540
It's not like I've already thought about a wedding and three kids and two hamsters named

53
00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:08.540
Invite him!

54
00:03:08.540 --> 00:03:09.540
Invite him!

55
00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:10.540
Then, okay.

56
00:03:10.540 --> 00:03:15.420
Ah, Marinette.

57
00:03:15.420 --> 00:03:17.980
Hello, Adrian.

58
00:03:17.980 --> 00:03:19.940
Are you free for lunch on Sunday?

59
00:03:19.940 --> 00:03:20.940
I...

60
00:03:20.940 --> 00:03:23.940
No, I already have something planned.

61
00:03:23.940 --> 00:03:27.260
Oh, is it something important?

62
00:03:27.260 --> 00:03:28.260
I'm meeting my grandparents.

63
00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:29.260
Wow!

64
00:03:29.260 --> 00:03:30.260
That's amazing!

65
00:03:30.260 --> 00:03:31.260
What?

66
00:03:31.260 --> 00:03:32.260
I'm not sure.

67
00:03:32.260 --> 00:03:35.260
I don't know them.

68
00:03:35.260 --> 00:03:37.660
I never even met them before.

69
00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:38.660
Seriously?

70
00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:41.860
My mom's parents, she didn't want us to see them.

71
00:03:41.860 --> 00:03:42.860
Huh?

72
00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:44.260
But, why not?

73
00:03:44.260 --> 00:03:45.260
She said they were mean.

74
00:03:45.260 --> 00:03:48.260
As for my father, he never even told me about his parents.

75
00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:49.260
Wow.

76
00:03:49.260 --> 00:03:52.260
And now, all of a sudden, they're determined to see me.

77
00:03:52.260 --> 00:03:54.260
I don't know what to do.

78
00:03:54.260 --> 00:03:57.260
You know how much I'd love to spend Sunday with you.

79
00:03:57.260 --> 00:03:58.260
Me too.

80
00:03:58.260 --> 00:03:59.260
But, you know what?

81
00:03:59.260 --> 00:04:02.260
Since you can't come to my place, I'll come to yours!

82
00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:03.260
I'm an expert at grandparents.

83
00:04:03.260 --> 00:04:07.980
I'm sure they're not that bad, and if they really are mean, then I'll protect you because

84
00:04:07.980 --> 00:04:08.980
you're family.

85
00:04:08.980 --> 00:04:09.980
Well, not yet.

86
00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:10.980
Uh, I mean, almost.

87
00:04:10.980 --> 00:04:11.980
What do you say?

88
00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:16.980
If that's possible, then I think I'd like you to be there with me.

89
00:04:16.980 --> 00:04:17.980
Yes.

90
00:04:17.980 --> 00:04:18.980
Of course it's possible.

91
00:04:18.980 --> 00:04:19.980
You'll see.

92
00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:20.980
Give me Natalie.

93
00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:23.740
I'm really not sure this is a good idea.

94
00:04:23.740 --> 00:04:27.460
Lord Graham was very specific about the lunch being a family-only reunion.

95
00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:29.780
Only the waitstaff will be allowed inside the dining room.

96
00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:31.860
Hence, the uniform.

97
00:04:31.860 --> 00:04:35.020
The shellfish cracker goes to the right of the fish fork.

98
00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:36.020
Oops.

99
00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:38.220
Lord Graham is a stickler for principals, Marinette.

100
00:04:38.220 --> 00:04:39.660
You'll have to be very discreet.

101
00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:43.460
I've done this plenty of times, helping my parents when they've catered events.

102
00:04:43.460 --> 00:04:44.460
I'll be invisible.

103
00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:46.940
I'm counting on the two of you to let me know how it went.

104
00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:47.940
Uh-huh.

105
00:04:47.940 --> 00:04:48.940
What do you mean?

106
00:04:48.940 --> 00:04:50.300
You're not having lunch with us?

107
00:04:50.300 --> 00:04:52.020
I'm not part of the family.

108
00:04:52.020 --> 00:04:53.020
What?

109
00:04:53.020 --> 00:04:56.660
Does Lord Graham know that you're practically Adrian's mom now?

110
00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:05.940
I could never replace Adrian's mother.

111
00:05:05.940 --> 00:05:10.860
These are your grandparents on your mother's side, Emile and Millie Graham de Vignilly.

112
00:05:10.860 --> 00:05:12.380
It's an honor to have you.

113
00:05:12.380 --> 00:05:13.380
You're not having us.

114
00:05:13.380 --> 00:05:16.900
May I remind you that this estate used to be our Pierre de Terre in Paris before we

115
00:05:16.900 --> 00:05:19.460
allowed our daughter and her dressmaker husband to live here.

116
00:05:19.460 --> 00:05:23.820
Now, at least they produced a half-decent-looking child.

117
00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:26.340
Grandfather, grandmother.

118
00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:31.220
Lord Graham, please.

119
00:05:31.220 --> 00:05:35.780
And arriving now are your grandparents on your father's side, Johnny and Gabriel Grissette.

120
00:05:35.780 --> 00:05:41.540
Thanks for the invite, Your International Highnesses.

121
00:05:41.540 --> 00:05:44.140
Hello.

122
00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:49.300
I am Lord Emile Graham de Vignilly, Duke of Westchester Monster, and this is Lady Millie,

123
00:05:49.300 --> 00:05:50.300
my wife.

124
00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:52.140
I am Johnny, and this is Gabriel.

125
00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:57.140
We are not married, but like a convict of love, I am chained to her forever.

126
00:05:57.140 --> 00:05:58.140
Oh!

127
00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:05.540
Jumping, jagged, Adrian, I've been waiting for this day for so long.

128
00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:10.380
Or even more, darling, in person.

129
00:06:10.380 --> 00:06:13.780
What is this intriguing scent?

130
00:06:13.780 --> 00:06:14.780
It's vile.

131
00:06:14.780 --> 00:06:16.780
It is my Valentines.

132
00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:17.780
Delish.

133
00:06:17.780 --> 00:06:18.780
No.

134
00:06:18.780 --> 00:06:21.300
I made them myself.

135
00:06:21.300 --> 00:06:23.180
I got to eat these poppies up.

136
00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:27.260
Where is your cuisine?

137
00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:29.420
Save yourself the trouble, mon petit.

138
00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:30.900
Just show me the way.

139
00:06:30.900 --> 00:06:33.420
Enough time wasted with preposterous ceremonials.

140
00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:36.620
Our lunch is waiting.

141
00:06:36.620 --> 00:06:40.820
Ooh la la.

142
00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:44.820
Fancy schmancy.

143
00:06:44.820 --> 00:06:52.180
Voila, serenze avant.

144
00:06:52.180 --> 00:07:03.220
Dear relatives, not by choice, I should say, thank you for agreeing to this lunch, which

145
00:07:03.220 --> 00:07:07.460
will undoubtedly prove to be decisive in regard to the future of our families.

146
00:07:07.460 --> 00:07:09.820
The question that brings us together at this table is--

147
00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:12.660
Sorry, I forgot something.

148
00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:15.660
By all means.

149
00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:17.860
Thank you.

150
00:07:17.860 --> 00:07:18.860
Plagg.

151
00:07:18.860 --> 00:07:19.860
Plagg.

152
00:07:19.860 --> 00:07:20.860
Adrian.

153
00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:21.860
Marinette.

154
00:07:21.860 --> 00:07:25.860
I know this must be hard, but everything's going to be okay.

155
00:07:25.860 --> 00:07:26.860
You're right.

156
00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:31.620
It'll be okay.

157
00:07:31.620 --> 00:07:36.100
As I was saying, the question that brings us together today is, who will have custody

158
00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:37.980
of Adrian now that he's all alone?

159
00:07:37.980 --> 00:07:40.980
But Adrian isn't alone.

160
00:07:40.980 --> 00:07:46.820
Mr. Adrian is not alone in having some appetizers, I suppose.

161
00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:50.100
If I may, Lord Graham, I live with Natalie.

162
00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:52.420
She's an employee, not family.

163
00:07:52.420 --> 00:07:56.140
She has no legal right to care for you, unlike us.

164
00:07:56.140 --> 00:07:57.140
Your mother's parents.

165
00:07:57.140 --> 00:08:01.820
Emil, dearest, Natalie has known Adrian for so long that she's practically part of the

166
00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:02.820
family now.

167
00:08:02.820 --> 00:08:03.820
Millie, I'm talking.

168
00:08:03.820 --> 00:08:05.820
Keep your useless remarks to yourself.

169
00:08:05.820 --> 00:08:10.500
Shown on this crest, bearing the coat of arms of our family, the Graham de Venilis, have

170
00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:14.860
always been a stride, the Kingdom of England and the lamented Kingdom of France.

171
00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:15.860
Oh, that's funny.

172
00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:21.620
The doggy is sweeping the floor, and what does this little poem say?

173
00:08:21.620 --> 00:08:25.860
It's a wolf, and the poem is our family motto, but it matters not.

174
00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:30.540
This dual nationality is symbolized in this twin ring, passed from generation to generation

175
00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:32.140
to the eldest child.

176
00:08:32.140 --> 00:08:34.500
Is something burning?

177
00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:39.860
Oh, that's my Johnny, always playing with the fire.

178
00:08:39.860 --> 00:08:43.300
Mr. Adrian, could you come with me to the kitchen to check?

179
00:08:43.300 --> 00:08:45.340
Thank you very much.

180
00:08:45.340 --> 00:08:50.620
Natalie, there's no way Adrian can't go and live there with that lord.

181
00:08:50.620 --> 00:08:54.260
Marinette, that lord is his grandfather, and I have no right to...

182
00:08:54.260 --> 00:08:59.060
There must be something that can be done.

183
00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:00.420
What do you think about this?

184
00:09:00.420 --> 00:09:01.900
I don't want to leave Paris, Marinette.

185
00:09:01.900 --> 00:09:07.380
I don't want to leave you or Natalie, but they're my family.

186
00:09:07.380 --> 00:09:11.620
Coal, a northern specialty, isn't it?

187
00:09:11.620 --> 00:09:13.700
So then you eat it.

188
00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:14.700
That's not coal.

189
00:09:14.700 --> 00:09:15.700
That's my Valentino.

190
00:09:15.700 --> 00:09:16.700
Oops.

191
00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:17.700
Let me handle this.

192
00:09:17.700 --> 00:09:18.700
Marinette.

193
00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:25.700
No.

194
00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:30.820
Oh, Milly, are you actually going to taste this horror?

195
00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:34.740
It looks like there's still something edible inside.

196
00:09:34.740 --> 00:09:35.740
Very well then.

197
00:09:35.740 --> 00:09:38.700
Poison yourself if you want to, but I better not hear a peep out of you.

198
00:09:38.700 --> 00:09:41.060
Getting back to the matter at hand.

199
00:09:41.060 --> 00:09:48.980
Hand me the Gram's twin ring.

200
00:09:48.980 --> 00:09:54.660
Oh my, it's incredible.

201
00:09:54.660 --> 00:09:55.660
I don't believe this.

202
00:09:55.660 --> 00:09:56.660
Silence!

203
00:09:56.660 --> 00:09:57.660
What is it filled with?

204
00:09:57.660 --> 00:09:58.660
Morel.

205
00:09:58.660 --> 00:09:59.660
It's a fromage.

206
00:09:59.660 --> 00:10:00.660
What is it?

207
00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:01.660
Not allergic, I hope.

208
00:10:01.660 --> 00:10:02.660
Gabrielle, start the bike.

209
00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:03.660
We're taking you to the hospital.

210
00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:04.660
No, no, it's all right.

211
00:10:04.660 --> 00:10:05.660
This is just so, so delicious.

212
00:10:05.660 --> 00:10:06.660
Milly, be a dear and silent.

213
00:10:06.660 --> 00:10:11.260
As you're used to doing so well.

214
00:10:11.260 --> 00:10:18.360
As I was saying, it's time Adrienne and the twin ring came back to a...

215
00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:24.100
Adrienne, where is the twin ring?

216
00:10:24.100 --> 00:10:29.380
I gave it to you, Lord Graham.

217
00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:30.380
You.

218
00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:31.380
What?

219
00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:32.380
You.

220
00:10:32.380 --> 00:10:33.380
You're not eating your balladins, are you?

221
00:10:33.380 --> 00:10:34.380
Give me back the ring.

222
00:10:34.380 --> 00:10:35.380
Oh, I see.

223
00:10:35.380 --> 00:10:37.900
So now you're calling me a thief, huh?

224
00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:38.900
Hold on.

225
00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:39.900
Let's not get carried away.

226
00:10:39.900 --> 00:10:42.420
It has to be here somewhere.

227
00:10:42.420 --> 00:10:43.420
How?

228
00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:46.380
I'll look for it too.

229
00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:47.700
The twin ring.

230
00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:49.240
Not here.

231
00:10:49.240 --> 00:10:50.240
Not here either.

232
00:10:50.240 --> 00:10:52.900
No one is leaving this room until the twin ring is recovered.

233
00:10:52.900 --> 00:10:56.860
And in the meantime, you are going to sign this contract that will, one, give me full

234
00:10:56.860 --> 00:11:00.580
custody of Adrienne and, two, assure me that you will never try to see him again.

235
00:11:00.580 --> 00:11:01.580
That's monstrous.

236
00:11:01.580 --> 00:11:06.500
Why would you want to keep us from seeing these poor kiddos as we only just met?

237
00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:07.860
Listen up, my lord.

238
00:11:07.860 --> 00:11:12.180
If Adrienne should go away with someone, that someone is going to be us and definitely not

239
00:11:12.180 --> 00:11:14.020
a mean monsieur like yourself.

240
00:11:14.020 --> 00:11:19.220
My dear darling, what do we care about this ring and all these antiquated customs, really?

241
00:11:19.220 --> 00:11:22.140
Milly, for pity's sake, stay in your place.

242
00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:26.500
Why do you scream all the time?

243
00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:27.660
Whoopsie!

244
00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:31.500
Sorry, I'm such a klutz.

245
00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:34.100
I understand clearly how much do you want?

246
00:11:34.100 --> 00:11:35.680
You can keep your money.

247
00:11:35.680 --> 00:11:39.920
We didn't want it 16 years ago and we don't want it today either.

248
00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:41.500
Stop this charade already.

249
00:11:41.500 --> 00:11:43.260
You just want to raise the bid.

250
00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:45.220
Name your price now and be done with it.

251
00:11:45.220 --> 00:11:46.220
I'm not charading.

252
00:11:46.220 --> 00:11:47.220
You're charading.

253
00:11:47.220 --> 00:11:49.700
You think I don't know what you've been up to this whole time?

254
00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:50.700
Come on, be honest.

255
00:11:50.700 --> 00:11:54.100
Tell us why you want so badly we should sign your contract.

256
00:11:54.100 --> 00:11:55.820
Woof, woof.

257
00:11:55.820 --> 00:11:58.060
It's always about who can growl the loudest.

258
00:11:58.060 --> 00:12:01.660
Don't pretend like you don't realize how shameful it would be if people knew that Adrian's

259
00:12:01.660 --> 00:12:04.580
other grandparents were... were what?

260
00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:05.580
Come on, say it!

261
00:12:05.580 --> 00:12:07.820
Were the owners of a fried food establishment!

262
00:12:07.820 --> 00:12:08.820
So what?

263
00:12:08.820 --> 00:12:09.820
What's the problem?

264
00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:12.500
The Grassets have been in the French fry for more generations than the Grahams have had

265
00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:14.100
a broomstick on their crest.

266
00:12:14.100 --> 00:12:17.660
My ancestors served cornets of fries with piquisauce to parmantier himself.

267
00:12:17.660 --> 00:12:18.660
